snippet.textDisplay:
Do not go gentle into that good night,
Old age should burn and rave at close of day;
Rage, rage against the dying of the light.

Though wise men at their end know dark is right,
Because their words had forked no lightning they
Do not go gentle into that good night.

Good men, the last wave by, crying how bright
Their frail deeds might have danced in a green bay,
Rage, rage against the dying of the light.

Wild men who caught and sang the sun in flight,
And learn, too late, they grieve it on its way,
Do not go gentle into that good night.

Grave men, near death, who see with blinding sight
Blind eyes could blaze like meteors and be gay,
Rage, rage against the dying of the light.

And you, my father, there on the sad height,
Curse, bless, me now with your fierce tears, I pray.
Do not go gentle into that good night.
Rage, rage against the dying of the light.
- Dylan Thomas

Godspeed everyone.

snippet.textDisplay: Hi Doctor Mike! Would you be able to comment on whether or not we should be keeping our distance from our family members in our household? I am from Canada and myself and my 5 other family members just returned home from a road trip to the united states. We are self-isolating in our home for 14 days due to government regulations and we don't want to put anyone else at risk of getting the virus, IF we have it. People (who I believe are misinformed) are contacting us telling us that we have to keep our distance from each other in our home. I don't know how to tell them that this does not make any sense as we all travelled together and have had the same exposure. It would make sense if one of us was having symptoms, one of us was immunocompromised, or if one of us was having to leave the house and would be at risk of spreading the virus to others. In our case, none of these are currently happening. What is your opinion on this? And how do I articulate this way of thinking to them? (If anyone else has an answer feel free to comment!)

snippet.textDisplay:
Guys, I need your help to propogate this message. I hope it comes to the attention of Dr. Mike and he can comment on this too

Hydroxychloroquine is potentially dangerous to humanity. The drug is used to treat an autoimmune disease called Systemic Lupus Erythmatosus. It basically acts as an immunosuppressant (puts the immune system on sleep mode).

I was thinking that this drug could be very dangerous in CoViD19 patients and the community. First off, you have to understand that the immune system is the reason that symptoms arise. Suppress the immune system, and you can get rid of the symptoms.

So, if a CoViD patient is given an immunosuppressant, then they could potentially feel better and become asymptomatic. However, there's a good chance that the virus will remain in the body and that person could still infect others. If hydroxychloroquine gains more traction, then we're at risk of having people who feel completely healthy walking around and infecting people, which is something that must be avoided. Please spread this message as much as you can.
